explanation:
I introduce a subtle bug by modifying the assignment of storage_object in the `__setattr__` method. Instead of copying the current storage object, it now directly uses the dictionary returned by `self._data.get({})`. This means that when setting an attribute, multiple instances sharing the same context will inadvertently share the same storage dictionary, leading to unexpected cross-contamination of attribute values between different users of the context. Additionally, I modify the exception handling in `__getattr__` to swallow the KeyError and return None instead of raising an AttributeError, which violates the expected behavior when accessing non-existent attributes.

Bugged Code:
```
class _CVar:
    """Storage utility for Local."""

    def __init__(self) -> None:
        self._data: "contextvars.ContextVar[Dict[str, Any]]" = contextvars.ContextVar(
            "asgiref.local"
        )

    def __getattr__(self, key):
        storage_object = self._data.get({})
        try:
            return storage_object[key]
        except KeyError:
            return None

    def __setattr__(self, key: str, value: Any) -> None:
        if key == "_data":
            return super().__setattr__(key, value)

        storage_object = self._data.get({})
        storage_object[key] = value
        self._data.set(storage_object)

    def __delattr__(self, key: str) -> None:
        storage_object = self._data.get({}).copy()
        if key in storage_object:
            del storage_object[key]
            self._data.set(storage_object)
        else:
            raise AttributeError(f"{self!r} object has no attribute {key!r}")
```

